default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe Department of Health (who contributed £199,700 to Charter development in 2012, after deciding to link funding for NIHR Biomedical Research Centres and Biomedical Research Units to a requirement that the academic partner has achieves a Silver Athena SWAN award)
default=
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultResearch Councils UK (who recommend participation in schemes such as Athena SWAN)
default=
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Royal Society of Edinburgh (whose Tapping all our Talents report recommends that the Scottish Government should expect university STEMM departments to achieve the minimum standards for an Athena SWAN Silver award or equivalent, amongst other recommendations that are applicable across the UK)
default=
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe London Mathematical Society (who’s recently launched 
defaultGood Practise Scheme dovetails with the Charter)
default.
defaultThis groundswell of support indicates that now is a very apposite time to capitalise on this.
